To allow searching/filtering on a concatenated display column in ag-Grid, you can use a custom filter that searches for the search term in the concatenated string.

Here's an example of how to implement a custom filter for your concatenated display column:
```javascript
// Define the custom filter
function remarksFilter(params) {
  // Get the search term from the filter
  var filterValue = params.filter;

  // If there is no filter value, return all rows
  if (!filterValue) {
    return true;
  }

  // Get the concatenated remarks column value for the current row
  var remarksValue = params.data.remarksConcatenated;

  // Check if the search term is contained in the concatenated remarks value
  return remarksValue.toLowerCase().indexOf(filterValue.toLowerCase()) >= 0;
}

// Set the custom filter to the remarksConcatenated column
columnDefs: [
  {
    headerName: "Remarks",
    field: "remarksConcatenated",
    filter: 'agTextColumnFilter',
    filterParams: {
      filterOptions: ['contains'],
      textCustomComparator: remarksFilter
    },
    cellRenderer: function(params) {
      // Truncate the concatenated remarks value to 250 characters
      var truncatedValue = params.value.length > 250 ? params.value.substr(0, 250) + '...' : params.value;
      return truncatedValue;
    }
  },
  // Other column definitions...
]
```
In this example, we define a custom filter function `remarksFilter` that takes the `params` object and checks if the search term is contained in the concatenated remarks value for the current row. We set the custom filter function to the `textCustomComparator` property of the `filterParams` object.

We also set the `filter` property to `'agTextColumnFilter'` to use the built-in text filter, and set the `filterOptions` property to `['contains']` to allow the user to search for any substring in the concatenated remarks value.

Lastly, we define a `cellRenderer` function to truncate the concatenated remarks value to 250 characters and add ellipses at the end. This will ensure that the display column is truncated for the end user while still allowing the custom filter to search/filter on the full concatenated value.

