To make an HTTP request in JavaScript, you can use the built-in `XMLHttpRequest` object or the newer `fetch()` API.

Here's an example using `XMLHttpRequest`:
```javascript
const xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
xhr.open('GET', 'https://example.com/data');
xhr.onload = () => {
  if (xhr.status === 200) {
    console.log(xhr.responseText);
  } else {
    console.log('Error!');
  }
};
xhr.send();
```
This code creates a new `XMLHttpRequest` object, sets the HTTP method and URL, defines a callback function to handle the response when it's received, and sends the request.

And here's an example using `fetch()`:
```javascript
fetch('https://example.com/data')
  .then(response => {
    if (response.ok) {
      return response.text();
    } else {
      throw new Error('Network response was not ok.');
    }
  })
  .then(data => console.log(data))
  .catch(error => console.error(error));
```
This code uses the `fetch()` function to make a GET request to the specified URL. The response is a Promise, which is then parsed as text and logged to the console. If there is an error, it is caught and logged to the console.

